Those who smoke have a higher risk of losing teeth
Those who smoke harm not only the lungs, but also the teeth – this is suggested by a long-term study in Potsdam.
The good news is that with waiver, the risk decreases rapidly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is evidenced by a long-term study by an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutrition Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers had a 2.5 to 3.6 times higher risk of losing their teeth prematurely.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth failure are cavities and inflammation of the gums, the DIfE emphasizes.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors emphasize.
The relationship between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gum inflammation in smokers.
It is unclear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of cavities.
People who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take more than ten years for the risk to drop back to the level of non-smoking, first author Thomas Dietrich of the University of Birmingham said.
It is necessary to convince people to become non-smoking, said study director Heiner Boeing at DIfE: “Smoking reduces lifetime.”
Not smoking is good for the lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health until old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 are affected by toothlessness, the DIfE said.
Previous research has already indicated that smoking increases the risk of early tooth failure.
The new long-term study supports the findings.
