Metcash launches ground resilience campaign to combat Aldi invasion
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA stores from an Aldi march in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground resilience campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
While Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets strengthen their relationships with local food suppliers and build the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and marketing through social media, as well as through events such as Adelaide shows.
IGA dealers and suppliers jump on board, with brands such as ice cream manufacturer Simmo from Dunsborough, distributing samples in IGA stores and shop owners selling cheap South Australian Football League tickets to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29, when the wholesaler of food, alcohol and devices will carry out its annual investor strategy day.
There is a lot at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 percent of Metcash’s IGA store deals and generate higher profit margins than Metcash’s IGA network in the eastern states.
Purchasers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland – more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to about 14 percent in the eastern states.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will snap about five percent of the food market in these two states and take away all existing stakeholders, but mainly independent retailers, from sales.
According to a report published this week, analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales per year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 branches in SA and 30 in WA next year, making revenues of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in food and grocery stores and in Metcash’s high fixed-cost quantities could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and taxes, Mr. Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash loses market shares in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey conducted by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley expects Metcash’s sales in the food and food business to fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, reducing its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, lead fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of the Magellan Financial Group, told at a business dinner in Melbourne that Metcash is likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash refused to publicly respond to Mr. Douglass’ comments.
But it is assumed that a Metcash board member contacted Mr. Douglass last week.
IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and revenues from Metcash’s food and food trade, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, have fallen by 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operating debt reduction while at the same time pressing on sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler is resisting and investing more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths at hundreds of products each week and to improve IGA retailers in improving their stores by fast-growing fresh food and delivering a better selection of private label foods.
Metcash’s chief executive Ian Morrice says the price adjustments and store remediation programs will increase to Elan and hopes that the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis supported by Australian Tennis Association President Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behaviour.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damages" in the recent storm around his friend Nick Kyrgios and deserves more praise than criticism for his own behavior, according to Australian tennis association president Steve Healy.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks", came into the spotlight by Kyrgio's infamous confrontation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fierce qualifying game in Cincinnati soon afterwards, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison shouting, "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should have beaten the child."
While he was last seen crushing a tennis racket after a crash defeated a potential US open victory by Richard Gasquet, Healy's Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the single after Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-finals against the UK.
"One thing I'm pretty jealous about is the fact that, in my opinion, Thanasi was slightly drawn into the dispute," Healy said.
He broke a racket when he lost in the US Open due to a cramp, but he is not the first player to break a racket out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he is not proud of it.
But, really, he behaved extremely well at the US open, even in the fairly provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I think he was treated a little too strictly.
He’s a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he has never had a problem with the other players, he’s being respected in the dressing room, he’s trained hard, he’s good in shape, he’s a very stable and mature young guy, and I think he deserves to be judged on his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision not to consider Kyrgios in the important preliminary decision that begins on Friday, and he describes the "common decision" as the right for everyone, but he assures the Canberra man to return to the team as a long-term solid part."
“First, we want the team to be fully focused on the competition and not all the controversies around [Kyrgios],” Healy said.
And I think Nick is very quick to achieve the ascent that people like Federer and Murray have pointed to. He is rising in the eyes of the public, and he has made some terrible mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we are trying to support him, we are trying to make him understand the consequences of his actions. Some time outside the rampage, and I can think of him as the best man.
Europe’s refugee crisis: Hungary declares emergency, closes the border, holds refugees back
Hungary declared emergency and closed the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday and held all those trying to get into the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border as hundreds of migrants accumulated in a no-man land and Serbian officials reacted with outrage.
The people who had fled from violence stood for an unknown time in a land strip on the road between the two control points of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations increased.
As a police helicopter floated over them, the migrants shouted "Open the border!" and cried insults against the Hungarian police.
Some rejected food and water from protest.
Serbia’s Foreign Minister said it was “unacceptable” that migrants from Hungary would be returned while more and more arrived from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
Talks will have to take place in the coming days with Brussels and other countries," Ivica Dacic said in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation block at a controversial meeting in Brussels failed to agree on common immigration policy.
However, the ministers agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in the overcrowded Italy and Greece, expressing their hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that the EU countries would welcome another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
Federal Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria on Tuesday called for a special EU summit to discuss the continent’s immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not put its hopes on soon action from Brussels or its neighbours.
The emergency situation in two southern regions declared Tuesday gave authorities more powers to cope with the crisis, allowing them to shut down roads and accelerate asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said his country is also planning to build a spinning wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country after it has finished a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prisoners were employed in the race to build the spinning wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a major congestion and an entry point to the European Union for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
Prime Minister Viktor Orban, however, insisted that the majority of incoming economic refugees are in search of a better life, not war refugees entitled to protection – a view that is strongly contrary to other EU countries, including Germany.
The new laws, which entered into force in Hungary at midnight, make crossing the border or damaging the four-meter (13-foot) fence that the government had built along the southern border with Serbia a crime. These laws also impose higher prison sentences for convicted human traffickers.
"Due to the situation arising from mass migration, the Hungarian government declares the state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: Illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament still has to agree to the military's deployment, which is expected for next week, but reporters from Associated Press have seen heavily armed soldiers on the border with vehicles and dogs for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, country security adviser for Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, 15 others had already invaded the country deeper.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police detention and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are about to repair the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a wagon with spindle wire arrived to close the borders.
Chaos surrounded the most important border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process human data and pressed a crowd to push into it.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway connection of Serbia and Hungary and said they would deny food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
