This will happen when the Fed increases interest rates.
An increase in interest rates will come, and the rise will fall, yields for bonds will rise, and the economy will glide into a recession.
We know that.
What we do not know is how long it will last and how long it will last.
In particular, the history provides little guidance for the economy on how to proceed.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate increase and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial investments react.
Therefore, the U.S. Central Bank’s representatives have so strongly emphasized that investors should not focus on when it starts to raise interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants could notice that the whole excitement was possibly overwhelmed due to an increase in interest rates.
“The first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal to the end of the “cheap money” era,” said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a statement to customers.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal heights, but still at too low levels to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here is a look based on historical trends on how some areas of the economy could react:
As the market has seen last month, anticipating interest rate increases can make things volatile for a while.
As soon as the increase arrives, the influence is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency for asset income to be stifled 12 to 24 months after the first increase, perhaps again reflecting the delay in monetary policy,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after the Fed’s interest rate increases.
More specifically, in the past 35 years, the market is mostly in the upward trend - about 14 percent - on its way to interest rate increases, quite flat in the 250 days afterwards (average profit of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the past six cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a recent analysis, the Bob Doll's chief investment rate at NuveAs.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on the stocks tends to occur later in the increase cycle and the return begins to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate increases often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is facing some conditions that did not exist before and could accelerate a recession.
Extremely remarkable here is that the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point when the Fed increases interest rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 interest rate increases since 1950 were only twice the nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect it to last and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest increases in such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky, raising the question “whether it’s different this time,” the Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been preparing for a Fed interest rate hike all year round, and all eyes were aimed at this week’s Federal Open Market Committee meeting that ends Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading indicates only a 25 percent probability.
"In our study, all increase cycles from 1950 to today took place in a super cycle with increasing growth in GDP and set pre-recession heights in shadows very quickly after the start of recovery," the report said.
In contrast, this is clearly a slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has been waiting for since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
The fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an increase in interest rates, and the pattern is quite similar to the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic price.
For bonds, returns seem to change the direction as soon as the first increase/decrease occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the raising cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab’s strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will bring returns closer together between longer and shorter bonds and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-income bonds often bring better yields in such a climate, although "we are still cautious of expecting higher yields," Kathy Jones, Schwab's fixed-income analyst, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones says that markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of stricter monetary policy," she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit margins have expanded, and volatility has increased – all characteristics of the market as the Fed exacerbates its strategy.
Companies operating the larger part of their business in the United States will benefit from rising interest rates and getting local products more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debt will be worse as a rise in the dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market and also the financing of their debt.
"The story shows that 'quality' stocks tend to react extremely positively three months after an initial rate increase," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Companies with a strong balance sheet surpassed companies with a low balance sheet by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital yields and low volatility in their shares also exceeded their counterparts with low quality by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt is a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see profits from higher yields, even if experts disagree about how quickly this will happen.
