The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the economic interests of the nation above all other things.
The central bank has a double order from Congress: Maximizing US employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the great recession, the Fed leaders have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X-factor in a decision that is too tight to predict, and it will be announced on Thursday whether the US economy is ready to start off the unprecedented incentive of the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Although most of the economy’s data shows that it’s growing solid, recent turmoil in global financial markets could make already cautious Fed representatives worry about increasing this volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds – even by just a quarter percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be primarily the most important thing they’re observing,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage company Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
