It would be a surprise if the Fed would raise the rates at that time,” he said.
If she does, she "must go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so they don't panic."
Other experts argued that an increase in interest rates would calm financial markets because it would eliminate uncertainty about when the Fed will trade.
Even a month ago, the Fed seemed well on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the recovery in the US.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that despite the complaints of liberals that more economic progress would be needed, she expects an increase in the rate this year.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers to be full employment.
Salary increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation was constantly below the annual target of 2% of the central bank, Fed representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can handle higher interest rates and needs them because of tension in the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world crashed at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell below its peak in May by more than 16 percent, as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy would slow global growth.
The market has recovered slightly this month, with the Dow now nearly 10% below the high of May.
For Fed representatives, market turmoil influences the complex calculation of when to increase interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred over the past few weeks, they would pull the lines at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, Senior Research Fellow at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the U.S. Central Bank.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the US economy, and there's almost no reliable data describing the developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not one of the main concerns of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the world’s monetary agency.
The central bank’s influence has been enormous in recent years.
The mere hint by then-director Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could "narrow" its monetary expansion triggered confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of Envestnet Inc's Global Asset Management Strategy.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, noted this month that "the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that appear to be not linked to the economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, advocating for an increase in interest rates, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its lead rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions "despite limited noticeable impacts on growth in the U.S.," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed representatives reversed these cuts.
The Fed should put financial stability aspects first only during a serious crisis such as the market collapse in 2008, said Adam S. Posen, former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate-setting committee.
