For slightly overweight diabetics, weight loss surgery can be helpful.
The benefits of weight loss surgery for slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
It’s still too early to say whether slightly overweight people with diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those receiving non-surgical treatments.
"The mortality data takes a long time to show something," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery, who wrote a guide article on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss surgery or obesity surgery, use various methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, obesity surgery has proven to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in people who are obese with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a certain degree of weight in terms of height, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or more indicates that someone is overweight, and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from Taiwan’s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected in a study since 2007, comparing two types of obesity surgery – gastric bypass and gastric hose formation – to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were slightly obese.
The average BMI among those who underwent this surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in this study.
Meanwhile, BMI remained roughly equal to 29 in those who received non-surgical diabetes treatments.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% resolved diabetes completely and 28% partially.
In the medical-treated group, compared to this, diabetes completely dissolved at only one percent and in part at only about two percent.
In addition, the results in the controls of blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol "in general were better in the "surgical" group," the authors found.
The researchers also monitored patients' blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level fell from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the medical therapy group, it remained stable at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycemic control" - as reflected in the improved hemoglobin A1c level - did not reduce mortality in five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared average results for the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, the bypass surgery group lost more weight compared to the gastrorectomy group (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%), and more likely recorded complete overcoming of diabetes (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
