Videos on YouTube show how teenagers drink disinfectants only because of a cheap experience.
Teenagers allegedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to get a harder drink.
Younger children can be attracted by attractive fragrances of the disinfectants.
“A child doesn’t think this is bad for him,” Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand disinfectants) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with strawberry, grape and orange scents that are very appealing to children.
Hand disinfectants contain somewhere between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, few splashes can lead to alcohol poisoning.
“It’s highly concentrated alcohol,” Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison emergency call center at the University of Kansas hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansa City.
So, you wouldn’t let a sip of whisky stand, but people leave this hand disinfectant within reach of children, and if children come to it, then it’s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four splashes of strawberry-scenting hand disinfectant at school, was brought to an emergency room for treatment.
