Robot cars: Government wants pioneering role for Germany
According to the will of the German government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the transformation of the car.
On Wednesday, the Federal Cabinet decided on a strategy paper from the House of Minister of Transport Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which includes investments in the development of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt at the edge of the IAA auto fair about a "new mobility age".
Automated and connected driving will increase traffic safety and reduce traffic jams, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the topic with his colleagues from the G7 countries, who will also meet with industry representatives at the IAA.
The Ministry of Transport’s strategy paper emphasizes, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a swift transition to digital radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being developed on Highway 9 in Bavaria.
In order for the driver to be "not charged with additional liability risks", the federal government intends to "verify the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt it to the new developments".
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the maximum allowable speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 km/h.
The federal government also wants to promote a change to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
With automated driving, the car is increasingly taking the lead, the driver becomes more and more a passenger.
The technology is mainly based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study submitted by the Ministry of Economy, highly automated driving on highways will be technically possible by 2020.
However, driverless vehicles on public roads are to be expected “far after 2020.”
The value added in the field of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the Germany site is estimated by the authors of the study at around €8.4 billion for 2025.
“Digital networking of the car can lead to greater road safety and efficiency,” said SPD transport policyman Sören Bartol.
However, the issue of liability in case of accidents and the safety of drivers’ personal data must be clearly clarified.
However, Germans still see self-driving cars skeptical – much more than French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute presented on Wednesday on behalf of the testing organization Dekra concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent expect it only in 20 years, 31 percent do not believe at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, while in the US, 33 percent.
However, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to give up control throughout the ride on all roads.
On the highway, 15 per cent of traffic could be imagined in flowing traffic, 45 per cent in traffic jams.
More than one in four would not be left to the car under any circumstances.
