Xi urges to open the economy broader to the world
The economy needs to open up more broadly to promote growth, President Xi Jinping said Tuesday to a group commissioned to steer the reform.
“China should be committed to attracting foreign investment and know-how and improving strategies for start-up business,” he said in an address at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group to deepen a comprehensive reform.
Fostering new start-ups and pushing forward reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership group has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list to regulate market access, relax border control policies, promote state enterprises (SOE), raise private capital, and revise the resident reporting system.
Following the statement, a negative list is created that identifies sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually tested and improved by testing programs.
The initiative is important because it assigns a greater role to the market in the allocation of resources, ensures a legally governed business environment and makes the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls over the powers conferred on companies and ensure that companies decide how to run their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of an offer to open government-controlled sectors, further areas for private investment will be opened.
“The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide better services to them,” the statement said.
In addition, it will make it easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the "Green Card" by optimizing the requirements and facilitating the application process.
The right of lawyers to carry out their duties and to employ professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at a meeting.
