EU wants to double the limit of mercury in prey fishing
The European Commission intends to double the limits for mercury in large predatory fish, giving consumers a significantly higher dose of the nerve poison.
The consumer organization Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, sharply criticized the plans: “Risks and side effects of missed industrial and environmental policies are being spread to pregnant women and toddlers with full force,” said Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of the nerve poison for large fish at the end of the food chain such as shark or swordfish for "economic policy reasons" should be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish.
However, large prey fish are already so heavily exposed to mercury that on the basis of the limits still in force, about 50 percent of the catches cannot be sold.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unsold.
According to Foodwatch, in return for this easing, the EU intends to increase the limit values for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch called this a “trick” because smaller friedfish, such as carps, are usually so lowly loaded that they already meet the planned maximum levels today.
The reduction of small fish is therefore “a perfide distraction maneuver that alone helps the economy,” Wolfschmidt said.
Mercury is a highly human-toxic heavy metal that is heavily enriched throughout the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The federal government warns that “already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn children”.
However, the Federal Environment Ministry declares on its homepage with regard to the existing maximum levels that a "health risk to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury comes into the environment primarily through coal combustion.
According to a written report by the Federal Environment Ministry, the German coal power plants release more than six tonnes of mercury per year, two-thirds of the total quantity emitted in Germany.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in Elbe, the Rhine and the Danube, was "permanently exceeded and extensively exceeded," the "mirror" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, European-wide warnings of mercury in fish were already among the most commonly reported health risks in the EU RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against the EU’s plans: www.quecksilver-aktion.foodwatch.de
